Referential integrity
for databases -> as users can be given different access rights, to either query or search, or delete and manipulate records
Multiple transactions occur
-> could lead to inconsistent databases
The Database Management system makes sure it is consistent
Through DATA INTEGRITY
'Maintenance and consistency of data in a database' 
Ensuring data integrity in a relational database is known as referential integrity
Removing employee:
- Delete record in the employee_details table
- then remove from employee_salary -> could lead to errors
This can be made worse if they are referenced in other tables.
INCONSISTENT DATA ^
one way to maintain it, is to have 'cascade delete'
- Means that if an employee is deleted from one table, all references to it are also deleted
Referential integrity, also means that  you cannot add a record if there is no matching reference in another table

TRANSACTION PROCESSING
any information processing that is divided into individual 'transactions'
Create
Read
Update
Delete

Atomicity - either all of the data goes through, or none of it does. this means there cannot be any partially saved data
Consistency - Any changes on a database must keep the database structure
Isolation - you can only perform 1 transaction at a time, so another transaction cannot interrupt a currently ongoing one (RECORD LOCKING)
Durability - Once a change is made, it must not be lost due to a system failure.
